post_text:
At the beginning of this strange, unprecedented Teacher Appreciation Week, The Greene School's PTSO wants to honor our teachers with a native Dogwood tree which will be planted in TGS's Arboretum.

We hope that when this tree blossoms around this time every year in the future, you will remember the 2020 school year and know that your students and their parents have seen you go above and beyond to make distance learning the best it can be for everyone. It is hard, hard work and we appreciate every minute that you spend helping our children learn and grow while they are outside your physical classroom. A donation has also been made in your honor to the National Arbor Day Foundation to spread the love and care you show our students and our natural world to other places in need of that care.

Thank you again for all you do. #WeAreCrew
text:
At the beginning of this strange, unprecedented Teacher Appreciation Week, The Greene School's PTSO wants to honor our teachers with a native Dogwood tree which will be planted in TGS's Arboretum.

We hope that when this tree blossoms around this time every year in the future, you will remember the 2020 school year and know that your students and their parents have seen you go above and beyond to make distance learning the best it can be for everyone. It is hard, hard work and we appreciate every minute that you spend helping our children learn and grow while they are outside your physical classroom. A donation has also been made in your honor to the National Arbor Day Foundation to spread the love and care you show our students and our natural world to other places in need of that care.

Thank you again for all you do. #WeAreCrew

Pi is defined as the ratio of a circle’s circumference to its diameter. Denoted by the Greek letter π, this curious little number is approximately 3.14, although computers have calculated it out past 22 trillion digits and counting: 3.141592653589793238462643383279502…, a sequence never repeating, never betraying any pattern, going on forever, infinity on a platter.

In every field of human endeavor... It all began with the computation of pi... it is an aspiration toward the perfect curve, steady progress toward the unreachable star. It exists, clear as night, with no end in sight. #NYTimes #TGSmathletes #10years

post_text:
Gr. 9 Learning Expedition: Food and Justice for ALL

Through an exploration of local and global food systems, students investigate the most compelling challenges related to feeding the world in the 21st Century.

Students explored the question: how can we sustain our growing human population in a way that is equitable to current and future generations? "Food insecurity is affecting everyone around the world. This expedition opened my eyes to the lack of food benefits people have both globally and locally. Now I feel we can make a difference."-Marques White, Gr. 9
#learningexpeditions #eleducation

post_text: This morning Will Malloy, a senior at Moses Brown, spoke to the TGS community about his experience as a member of the transgender community. Will, a recent recipient of the Equality Award from the Human Rights Campaign, spoke from the heart about his struggles and triumphs as well as ways in which communities can foster empathy and acceptance for all. Will's advocacy for the transgender community was inspiring and moving. We are grateful he came to share his experiences with us, and his words will stay with us. Thank you, Will!

post_text:
Each winter students participant in an elective short-course, called an “intensive.” These courses take place between the fall and spring semesters so there is no other instruction at that time. This allows students and teachers to do a deep dive into topics that otherwise fall outside our typical curriculum.

Check out this mission aligned intensive:

Shark Week: Throughout this intensive, students will learn about sharks, and their increasing presence on the east coast. Sharks are one of the most diverse species on earth, with around 465 different species, but many myths exist that make them one of the most misunderstood species which challenges conservation efforts. Through research, expert speakers, service learning, and hands on activities, including dissection, students will come to their own conclusions surrounding the causes of shark attacks and shark protection.

post_text:
Our Place by the Sea is a semester-long expedition focused on coastal resilience and sustainability that engages students as environmental leaders through detailed data collection and analysis. Throughout the Fall Semester, with the generous support of The Island Foundation, TGS Seniors have been able to engage in a hands on exploration of the urgent environmental issues and remediation efforts occurring in the coastal communities of Rhode Island. Last Friday, students presented their research projects at the Coastal Resource Center at The URI Bay Campus. The students did an outstanding job! Congratulations!

We would also like to extend our gratitude to Block Island Maritime Institute, Save the Bay, and the Coastal Resource Center for helping us design powerful learning experiences for our students.

post_text: Last Thursday the Freshman class hosted a Food Justice Symposium as their Expedition Final Product at the University of Rhode Island. They held three simultaneous table top Socratic seminars with local experts including a TGS board member and alumni, two URI Professors, and a Rhode Island state legislator. The months of preparation and fieldwork prepared the 9th grade to be informed, vocal, solutions-oriented advocates for equity in food security, both locally and globally. We could not be more proud!
